[normal]D. [bold]Your Questions[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Question One - How resilient are the [bold]UK[bold]’s transport networks (including road, rail and air) to adverse winter weather?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Adverse weather
[normal] - weather that is bad but not unusual
[normal]. In winter the definitions include more than 2cm of snow in 
[normal]London
[normal] and the southeast or 5cm elsewhere with a warning about accumulation or drift risk, 60mph winds or temperatures below -3ºC. 
[normal]All
[normal] normal
[normal] years have periods of adverse weather. 
[normal]During adverse weather the 
[normal]industry plans to run a full service but punctuality may be a fe
[normal]w PPM points lower than 
[normal]on a normal day
[normal];
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Extreme weather
[normal] - rare weather that is seen once every ten or twenty years
[normal]. In winter this is defined as more than 15cm snow, 70mph winds and temperatures below -7
[normal] 
[normal]ºC. 
[normal]During extreme weather the industry seeks to ensure all
[normal] 
[normal]customer journeys are completed safely
[normal], and punctuality is not prioritised. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
